## Summary

I added a new `WeatherTool` agent tool following the repo's existing patterns exactly as documented in `AGENT_CALL_PATH.md`:

### 1. Created `WeatherTool.java` (in `com.tepeu.agent.tool`)
A `@Component` class with a `@Tool(name = "get_weather")` method that takes a `city` string and returns a short fake weather string — no HTTP involved:

```java
@Tool(name = "get_weather", description = "Return a short fake weather string for a city. ...")
public String getWeather(@ToolParam(description = "...") String city) {
    if (city == null || city.isBlank()) {
        return "ERROR: city required";
    }
    return "The weather in " + city.trim() + " is sunny and 22°C (fake data).";
}
```

This mirrors the structure of the sibling `FileTools` / `ShellTools` (same package, `@Component`, `@Tool` + `@ToolParam` annotations, `String` return type, defensive null/blank handling).

### 2. Registered it in `Tools.java`
Added `WeatherTool weatherTool` as a constructor parameter to the `toolRegistry` `@Bean` method and a `registry.register("weatherTool", weatherTool)` line — the single registration point this repo uses.

### Why `ChatService` didn't need changes
`ChatService.streamWithTools` already reads tools generically via `toolRegistry.beans()` and passes them through `ToolCallbacks.from(...)`, so the new tool is automatically exposed to the model with no edits there. This keeps the change minimal and consistent with the documented "新增工具：实现类 + 在本文件 register 一行" workflow.

The project compiles cleanly (`mvn -q -DskipTests compile` → exit 0).
